<DOC><DOCNO> AP890213-0228 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1002EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-MiddleEast-Economy     02-13 0141</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Middle East-Economy,0146</SECOND><HEAD>Four Arab Countries Reach Accord on Economic Grouping</HEAD><DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Egypt, Jordan, North Yemen and Iraq haveagreed to form an economic alliance patterned after the EuropeanEconomic Community, diplomats said Monday.   They said representatives of those countries will meet in Jordanon Tuesday to put the final touches on the agreement, and the headsof state are expected to sign the accord Thursday.   Officials in the four countries have said the Arab EconomicCooperation Council would enhance economic ties and lead to morecooperation in number of fields, including industry, transportation,agriculture, electricity and scientific research.   ``With a population of 80 million and vital strategic andpolitical influence, the new group will be a major block which allother Arab countries ... should reckon with,'' said one Asiandiplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity.</TEXT></DOC>